Data Privacy Policy

1. Introduction
The purpose of this Data Privacy Policy is to define how customer information is collected, stored, protected, and deleted. The company is committed to safeguarding personal data in accordance with all applicable laws and industry standards.

2. Data Collection
The company collects only the minimum necessary personal data required to deliver services. This includes account information, contact details, and usage activity. Sensitive information is collected only when required for regulatory compliance.

3. Data Encryption
All customer data must be encrypted both at rest and in transit using industry-standard encryption protocols. At rest, AES-256 encryption is required for all databases and storage volumes. For data in transit, TLS 1.2 or higher is mandatory across all internal and external communication channels.

4. Access Control
Customer data may only be accessed by authorized personnel with a legitimate business purpose. Access must be granted using role-based permissions. All access activity must be logged, timestamped, and retained for audit review for a minimum of 12 months.

5. Data Sharing
Customer information may not be

shared with third parties unless the customer has provided explicit consent or the sharing is required to fulfill a legal obligation. Any approved data transfer must be encrypted and follow the same security standards defined in this document.

6. User Rights
Customers have the right to request access, correction, deletion, or export of their personal information. All requests must be fulfilled within 30 days.

7. Violation Reporting
Any suspected data privacy violation must be reported to the Security Office within 24 hours. Incidents that involve customer information require immediate escalation to the Compliance Team.

End of Policy

Data Retention Policy

1. Purpose
The purpose of this policy is to define the required retention period for customer data, internal records, logs, and backups.

2. Customer Data Retention
All customer data must be retained for a minimum of 7 years. Customer data includes personally identifiable information, account histories, communication logs, and contractual documents.

3. Backup Retention
All system backups must be securely archived. Backups must be retained for a minimum of 5 years unless additional retention is required by regulatory frameworks. Backups may only be deleted after both retention and audit requirements are met.

4. Log Retention
Application logs, authentication logs, and administrative activity logs must be retained for at least 12 months. High-risk systems require logs to be retained for 24 months.

5. Secure Disposal
Data that has exceeded its retention period must be disposed of securely. Acceptable disposal methods include cryptographic erasure, secure file deletion tools, and physically destroying storage media. Disposal actions must be documented.

6. Suspension of Disposal
If data is subject to litigation, investigation, or audit, the di

sposal of such data must be suspended regardless of the retention schedule.

End of Policy

Mobile Device Usage Policy



1. Purpose

The purpose of this Mobile Device Usage Policy is to establish rules and expectations for the secure and responsible use of mobile devices when accessing company data or systems. This policy applies to all employees, contractors, and third-party personnel.



2. Scope of Allowed Devices

The company allows the use of approved mobile devices for work purposes. Allowed devices include:

 Company-issued smartphones

 Company-issued tablets

 Personally owned mobile devices enrolled in the Mobile Device Management (MDM) system



Unapproved or jailbroken devices are strictly prohibited from accessing company resources.



3. Security Requirements

All mobile devices used for work must meet the following requirements:

a. Device lock: A PIN, password, fingerprint, or biometric lock must be enabled.

b. Encryption: Devices must support full-disk encryption and have it enabled.

c. MDM Compliance: Personal devices must remain enrolled in the companys MDM system and comply with all enforced security rules.

d. OS Updates: Employees must install critical operating system updates within 7 days of release.



4. Access to Company Systems

Employee

s may access company email, collaboration tools, and internal applications through approved apps only. Access must be performed over secure connections, including HTTPS or the corporate VPN. Use of public Wi-Fi networks is discouraged unless combined with the VPN.



5. Data Storage and Handling

Employees may not store confidential or sensitive data on mobile devices unless:

 The device is company-issued, and

 The data is stored in approved, encrypted applications.



Screenshots of sensitive information are prohibited. Data must never be copied to personal cloud storage services.



6. Lost or Stolen Devices

Employees must report any lost or stolen mobile device within 12 hours. The IT Security Team may issue a remote wipe command on devices that are compromised or unreachable. Cooperation with the investigation is mandatory.



7. Application Restrictions

Only approved applications may be installed on devices used for work. Personal applications must not interfere with device performance or security. Installation of unverified third-party app stores is prohibited.



8. Termination of Employment

Upon employee separation, all company data must be removed from personal devi

ces. The IT department will verify the removal and unenroll the device from the MDM system.



9. Violations

Failure to comply with this policy may result in:

 Revocation of mobile device privileges

 Disciplinary action

 Reporting to Human Resources or Compliance

 Possible legal action if sensitive data is compromised

Remote Work and Telecommuting Policy

1. Purpose
This policy outlines the requirements, expectations, and security standards for employees who perform their job duties from a remote location. The goal is to support flexible work arrangements while maintaining productivity, confidentiality, and data security.

2. Eligibility
Remote work arrangements must be approved by Human Resources and the employees direct manager. Approval depends on job role, performance history, and operational needs. Employees must maintain core working hours unless an alternative schedule is approved in writing.

3. Equipment and Technology
The company provides approved equipment for remote work, which may include laptops, monitors, headsets, and docking stations. Personal devices may not be used to access company systems unless explicitly permitted by the IT Security Team.

4. Secure Connection Requirements
All remote access to company systems must occur through the corporate VPN. The VPN must be active at all times while handling company data. Public or unsecured Wi-Fi networks may only be used in combination with the corporate VPN.

5. Data Handling and Confidentiality
Employees are respon

sible for maintaining the confidentiality of company information in remote environments. Printed documents containing sensitive information must be stored securely or shredded after use. Screen privacy filters are required when working in public spaces.

6. Workspace Expectations
Remote workspaces must be safe, clean, and free from excessive noise. Employees should have a dedicated work area to maintain productivity. The company reserves the right to revoke remote work privileges if workspace conditions interfere with performance.

7. Incident Reporting
Any security incident, equipment loss, suspected malware infection, or unauthorized access attempt must be reported to the IT Security Team within 24 hours. Remote workers must comply with follow-up investigations and corrective actions.

8. Performance Expectations
Employees working remotely must meet or exceed normal performance standards. Failure to meet expectations may result in a return to on-site work or disciplinary action.

End of Policy

Security Standards and Practices Policy

1. Overview
This policy establishes the minimum security standards required to ensure the confidentiality, integrity, and availability of company systems and data.

2. Authentication Requirements
All users must authenticate using multi-factor authentication (MFA). Passwords must be at least 12 characters long and include a mix of uppercase, lowercase, numeric, and symbolic characters. Passwords must be rotated every 180 days.

3. Network Security
The corporate network must be segmented to isolate sensitive systems. Firewall rules must follow a deny by default posture. All inbound and outbound network traffic must be monitored by the Security Operations Center.

4. Logging and Monitoring
All systems must forward logs to the centralized monitoring platform. Logs must include authentication attempts, configuration changes, administrative actions, and access to sensitive records. Logs must be retained for a minimum of one year.

5. Patch Management
All server and endpoint operating systems must be patched within 30 days of security updates becoming available. Critical vulnerabilities must be patched within 72 hours. A vulnerabil

ity scan must be performed weekly.

6. Incident Response
All employees must follow the established Incident Response Plan. Incidents must be classified according to severity and escalated to the Incident Response Team. Post-incident reviews are mandatory within 7 days of resolution.

End of Policy
